Here's a function in JavaScript that takes an array of 5 numbers as input and checks if any of the numbers is a valid prime number. If it is, it prints the number to the console:
```javascript
function checkPrimeNumbers(arr) {
  for (let i = 0; i < arr.length; i++) {
    let num = arr[i];
    if (isPrime(num)) {
      console.log(num);
    }
  }
}

function isPrime(num) {
  if (num <= 1) {
    return false;
  }
  for (let i = 2; i < Math.sqrt(num); i++) {
    if (num % i === 0) {
      return false;
    }
  }
  return true;
}

const arr = [3, 5, 12, 11, 15];
checkPrimeNumbers(arr);
```
In this example, the `checkPrimeNumbers` function takes an array of 5 numbers as input. It then iterates over the array using a `for` loop and calls the `isPrime` function for each number. If the `isPrime` function returns `true` for a number, it will print the number to the console.

The `isPrime` function checks if a number is prime by iterating from 2 up to the square root of the number. If a number is divisible by any of these numbers, it is not prime, and the function returns `false`. If it reaches the end of the loop without finding a divisor, the function returns `true`, indicating that the number is prime.

You can call the `checkPrimeNumbers` function with your own array of 5 numbers to see which ones, if any, are prime.

